'''Michael Kerrisk''' is a technical author, programmer and, since 2004, [[software maintainer|maintainer]] of the Linux [[man page|man-pages]] project,<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.kernel.org/doc/man-pages/ |title=The Linux man-pages project |publisher=[[kernel.org]] |accessdate=2014-05-01}}</ref> succeeding [[Andries Brouwer]].<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.kernel.org/doc/man-pages/maintaining.html |title=Maintaining Linux man-pages |publisher=[[kernel.org]] |accessdate=2014-05-01}}</ref> He was born in 1961 in [[New Zealand]] and lives in [[Munich, Germany]].

Kerrisk has worked for [[Digital Equipment]], [[Google]], [[The Linux Foundation]]<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.oreilly.com/pub/au/4367 |title=Michael Kerrisk - O'Reilly Media |publisher=[[O'Reilly Media]] | accessdate=2014-05-01}}</ref> and, as an editor and writer, for [[LWN.net]].<ref>{{cite web |url=https://lwn.net/Articles/549009/ |title = A goodbye note from Michael Kerrisk |publisher=[[LWN.net]] |accessdate=2014-05-01}}</ref> Currently, he works as a freelance consultant and trainer.

He is best known for his book ''[[The Linux Programming Interface]]'',<ref>{{cite web |url=http://man7.org/tlpi/index.html |title=The Linux Programming Interface |publisher=man7.org |accessdate=2014-05-01}}</ref> published by [[No Starch Press]]<ref>{{cite book |last= Kerrisk |first=Michael |title=The Linux Programming Interface |year=2010 |edition=1 |publisher=[[No Starch Press]] |isbn=978-1-59327-220-3}}</ref> in 2010. This book is widely regarded<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.amazon.com/The-Linux-Programming=Interface-Handbook/dp/1593272200 |title=Amazon's Readers Review |publisher=[[Amazon.com]] | accessdate=2014-05-01}}</ref> as the definitive work on Linux system programming and has been translated into several languages.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://man7.org/tlpi/translations/index.html |title=Translations of 'The Linux Programming Interface' |publisher=man7.org |accessdate=2014-05-01}}</ref>

As the [[software maintainer|maintainer]] of the Linux [[man page|man-pages]] project, Kerrisk has authored or co-authored about a third of the man pages and worked on improving the project's infrastructure. For his contributions he received a Special Award of the 2016 [[New Zealand Open Source Awards]].<ref>{{cite web | url=http://nzosa.org.nz/news-and-media/winners-of-the-2016-new-zealand-open-source-awards-announced/ | title=Winners of the 2016 New Zealand Open Source Awards Announced | accessdate=2016-11-12}}</ref>

